column168: A vehicle operated by Clean Harbors Environmental Services, Inc. was en route from the shippers location to Clean Harbor’s in transit storage location in  Baltomore MD for the purpose of consolidating less than truck load quantities of hazardous waste for continuing transportation to the intended waste management facility. While transferring one container, it was discovered that approximately 2 ounces of material escaped from the body of the container. Facility personnel placed the leaking container into a suitable salvage drum along with all clean-up debris from the van trailer. The container was secured and was sent for disposal to the intended waste management facility.
column169: At the time the driver accepted the container for transportation, no evidence of leaking was observed. The driver, however, was re-instructed to conduct a  thorough inspection of each container before acceptance and if any evidence of a reduction in structural integrity is found to take appropriate action to  either place the container into a suitable salvage drum or re containerize before transportation is initiated. In addition, the shipper was advised of the  incident and was requested to inspect all drums in current inventory for any containers with suspect integrity.The customer was also notified that they must use proper packaging procedures and drum types when packaging their hazardous waste.

column169: Both Employees will attend Buckley Powder Co SOP on DOT Special permit training, rollover prevention training, defensive driving training and HazMat awareness training before resuming commercial vehicle operations.

column168: The driver was drinking water while driving when some of the water traveled down windpipe causing the driver to choke and cough uncontrollably. The driver lost control of the truck and ended up plunging 200ft down an embankement. The truck and trailer rolled over causing the load (batteries, wet, filled with acid) to spill. Tri-State Environmental arrived on site and assessed the area, the crew utilized an excavator to stock pile the batteries and impacted debris away from the trailer so that the trailer could be removed by the towing company. The crew staged all impacted materials on poly sheeting and then boomed off the area to prevent any spreading of the battery acid. Tri State Environmental will remove impacted materials and transport it for proper disposal.
column169: The root cause of the release was due to the accident, Celadon has a policy that requires us to review the driver's safety record any time an accident occurs. Unfortunately accidents occur while individuals are driving each day, in this case there is nothing that the driver could have done to prevent the accident. Once we review the safety records, we will determine the required training that the driver will need as appropriate under Celadon's policy.

column168: On September 11, 2012 ERTS was contacted by R&L Carriers to manage a UN3109 Organic Peroxide release at the referenced location.  ERTS dispatched Northridge Group for initial response and cleanup.  The contractor reported that the drum was uprighted prior to their arrival. Apparently the drum tipped over and which damaged the container resulting in the release.  Northridge personnel neutralized and applied granular absorbents to the impacted areas.  The damaged drum was placed into an overpack and was transported back to R&L Carriers.  One 30 gallon drum of absorbent pads and a 20 gallon drum of organic peroxide impacted absorbents was generated from cleanup and was taken off site for disposal.

The driver reported that when he pulled out of the Flying J, he noticed a washout cap from the top of the cargo tank rolling along the side of the trailer.  he pulled over as soon as he could.  driver said that the caps were all tight when he picked up the load.  Not sure how much spilled but probably less than a gallon.  I inquired if there was a trail on the roadway and he said no.  He said there had been some on the outside of the cargo tank but it had evaporated.  A police officer was there and verified there was no need for a response team.  There was nothing to clean up.    Driver replaced washout cap. the officer had mentioned that they had prior issues with vandalism at the truck stop but not sure if that was the case this time. Driver was not cited.  The driver should still have verified the cap was tight before he left the Flying J.
column169: The driver received perfomance enhancement training stressing proper pretrip inspections.  We are addressing the issue of washout cap securement with all of our drivers during our 4th quarter training.

column168: The Transportation Services Unlimited Inc. (TSUI) cargo tanker, loaded with Allied Universal Corporation Sodium Hypochlorite (Bleach) product, was enroute from The Family Pools Company in Fort Walton Beach, Florida to another customer location Ace Hardware in Panama City, Florida for product delivery.  While in enroute, an unknown driver operator notified the driver of the TSUI cargo tanker that “something was leaking out of the top of his cargo tanker”.  The TSUI driver safely stopped his tractor-cargo tanker, and visually verified a leak from self-closing vent (called a Girard pressure relief vent) on top of the cargo tanker.  It was unknown to the driver how long the self-closing vent was leaking, however the TSUI driver had been on the road for “x” minutes.  As the TSUI driver was placing emergency triangles out, a Panama City Beach police officer stopped, and after visually noting the leak, called the Panama City Beach fire department to the scene.    Panama City Beach fire department confirmed the leaking liquid was Sodium Hypochlorite.  It has been estimated approximately “xxx” gallons of Sodium Hypochlorite had been released from the cargo tanker, spilling onto the cargo tanker.  The fire department washed down the cargo tanker and road with water.  Once the washing was complete, and the fire department as well as TSUI driver determined the cargo tanker was no longer leaking as the self-closing vent had resealed the TSUI driver and cargo tanker were released from the scene to continue delivery of the product.  Upon TSUI and Allied Universal Corporation joint investigation, it was determined that the TSUI driver failed to follow proper procedure for preparing the cargo tanker for shipment after delivery by failing to ensure the pressure in the cargo tanker was less than 22 psi.  His failure to properly follow procedure allowed the cargo tanker pressure to build while in transit, exceeding the maximum allowable working pressure of the pressure relief device, and leading to the release of Sodium Hypochlorite from the valve.
column169: 1) TSUI driver suspended during investigation  2) TSUI driver coached (special one-on-one training) on his mistake and how to    prevent this type of incident  3) Disciplinary action taken against the TSUI driver per company policy for his failure to follow company procedure  4) TSUI driver bonus for the quarter terminated do to driver being charged for the incident  5) All TSUI drivers at the Ellisville, Mississippi facility site underwent refresher training for proper cargo tanker delivery of Sodium Hypochlorite  6) TSUI Fleet Maintenance Manager is looking at additional devices to control the amount of pressure used to unload Sodium Hypochlorite cargo tankers so that pressure does not exceed the company policy of 22 psi.

column168: At approximately 2:00 PM on September 12, 2012 KCS mechanical personnel reported a strong odor emanating from tank car TILX 270325 containing UN1267 Petroleum Crude Oil.     Upon arrival and closer inspection of tank car TILX 270325, the responders determined that the odor source from the vacuum relief valve (VRV) under the dome housing. The VRV had been stuck partially open due to some dried/hardened lading residue (Crude Oil) in the valve pathway. The VRV was removed, residue cleaned out of VRV, and replaced back into tank car. The tank car passed a field leak test with 10 psi.     *No injuries were reported.    File Note Item 19 - the quantity released was estimated. The actual amount released from this container is unknown to the carrier. To determine actual amount released: contact the offeror to determine actual quantity in tank car at origin (if available), then contact  consignee to determine actual amount in tank car once unloaded (if available), and the difference will be the total amount released.     File Note: Item 27 - Amount in package was estimated by this report preparer because the exact information is not available to carrier. Shipper provided bulk quantity on shipping paper as 1 Tank Car, per DOT requirements.
column169: Recommendations:  The Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR) notified shipper of this release. Non Accidental Releases (NAR) can be devastating on several different levels. They can cause personal injury, environmental damage, disrupt rail yards, adjacent facilities and communities, and snarl train operations for hundreds of miles and both directions. NARs are troublesome to all because they are, by and large, preventable. For non accident releases (a.k.a. package closure defects such as this), the shipper is requested to conduct a root-cause investigation to determine the cause(s) of release and to then facilitate corrective action to prevent recurrence. It is requested that the shipper share their findings with KCS.     The Association of American Railroads (AAR) hazmat inspector (aka BOE inspector) will follow up to all Non Accident Releases (NAR) to assist hazmat shipper with regulatory requirements and training to help prevent recurrence of unsafe transportation conditions.    The shipper can reference http://nar.aar.com for help understanding and preventing NARs.

column168: Tank car AMCX 25812 was reported leaking product from the top fitting area while in the railyard. AMCX 28512 was cordoned off in the railyard. No released product impacted the ground. Inspection of AMCX 25812 by contract responders revealed the leak source was at the vacuum relief valve (VRV) that appeared to be stuck open. AMCX 25812 was deemed safe to move and it was isolated in the railyard. The responders removed the faulty VRV and securely installed a pipe plug in the vacated VRV orifice. All other valves and fittings were found secure. The product outage was checked and deemed appropriate. Intact shipper seals (048367, 048368) removed were replaced by seal 489496 at the valve housing cover and seal 1000937 at the manway closure. The small amount of spillage on the outer tank shell evaporated.

On September 19, 2012, ERTS was contacted by R&L Carriers to manage a UN1987 Ethyl Alcohol release inside of a trailer.  ERTS dispatched Eastern Environmental to perform cleanup activities and a tote transfer. Eastern personnel arrived onsite and reported that the elbow from the valve was leaking.  Eastern personnel successfully perform the tote transfer. The replacement tote and the damged tote were staged on the trailer to be transported back to R&L Carriers.  Eastern personnel utilized granular and absorbent pads to clean the trailer.  One drum of granular and absorbent pads was generated from cleanup and transported for disposal.

An intermodal box was picked up at the Port of Houston.  Upon arrival at the intended waste disposal facility, a small amount of liquid was leaking from a cut in the side of the steel box which had been covered with a strip of duct tape.  A response crew was summoned and temporarily patched the hole in order to process the box into the facility.  After donning the appropriate personal protective equipment, the leaked material (water and soil) was cleaned up with a suitable absorbent material and placed into the box.  The box then entered the facility without further incident.
column169: It appears that the box was shipped with the duct tape placed over the cut.  The driver at the Port of Houston noticed the tape but there was no leakage nor opportunity to investigate the cut at the port facility.  The origin location was sent photographs to investigate on their end why this was shipped with a temporary patch (strip of duct tape).

column168: A van trailer containing shipments of hazardous waste arrived at the intermediate truck transfer facility for consolidation into other trailers destined for various waste disposal facilities.  Upon opening the door, it was found that the floor was stained with spilled liquid from one of the flex bins. The flex bin had a 8" long cut in the side from a loose piece of metal along the side of the trailer.  A cleaning compound was used to clean the trailer floor and the flex bin was overpacked into a suitable salvage container.  The cleanup materials were also placed into the salvage container and it was loaded onto a trailer destined for the intended waste disposal facility without further incident.

column168: A FRA Hazardous Material Inspector observed motionless tank car NATX 301198 with a dried product stain on its outer tank shell that emanated from the manway closure. No active product leak was reported but the stain was indicative of a leaking manway during rail movement. Contract responders inspected NATX 301198. Responders reported no active liquid product release was found, only dried product residue staining on the tank shell. The manway closure was found secure and it was opened to inspect the manway gasket condition. The manway gasket was missing and a new gasket was installed. Afterwards, the manway was closed and manway securement bolts properly tool tightened. All other valves and fittings were found secure. Response was concluded by 1930 hrs. PDT, 9/10/2012.  Intact shipper seals 0515637 and 0515627 were replaced by seals 768500 and 768498 at the manway closure and valve housing cover respectively.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: THE TRAILER ARRIVED AT BNSF IN WILLOW SPRINGS, IL AND WAS REPORTED TO BE SMOKING AND LEAKING.  THE TRAILER WAS MOVED TO THE HAZMAT PIT WHERE THE FIRE WAS NOTICED.  THE CHICAGO FIRE DEPT PUT OUT THE FIRE AND REQUESTED TO HELP UNLOAD.  CONTRACTOR WAS DISPATCHED TO REMOVE THE FREIGHT FROM THE TRAILER.  THERE WERE 3 PALLETS OF DEAD BATTERIES THAT WERE RESPONSIBLE FOR THE FIRE AS THE METAL STRAPS HOLDING THE BATTERIES TO THE PALLETS TOUCHED THE NEGATIVE TO POSITIVE POST ON THE BATTERIES WHICH STARTED THE FIRE.  THE SHIPPER MARKED THE BATTERIES AS DEAD ON THE BILL OF LADING.  THEY SHOULD HAVE INDENTIFIED THESE AS UNIVERSAL WASTE AND OUR DRIVER WOULD NOT HAVE PICKED THEM UP.
column169: SHIPPER IDENTIFIED THE BATTERIES INCORRECTLY.  IF THEY WERE MARKED CORRECTLY AS UNIVERSAL WASTE THEN OUR DRIVER WOULD NOT HAVE PICKED UP THE FREIGHT AND THIS INCIDENT WOULD NOT HAVE OCCURRED.

column168: While stopping for a meal stop, the Veolia field service team noticed a small leak on the back of their straight truck. Upon investigating, the Veolia employees identified a 5 gallon container had tipped over while enroute as a result of several other containers shifting during transit. As a result a small amount of liquid leaked out of the closure of the container while it was on its side. The container was then uprighted, the closure retightened, the spill material was absorbed and placed into another container for proper disposal. The load was also resecured to prevent movement during the remaining transportion phase.
column169: This incident was review with field personnel at a safety meeting emphasizing the need to ensure containers are properly braced to prevent movement in any direction relative to the vehicle as well as to ensure all container closures are properly tightened in accordance with the closure instructions when specification packages are used.

column168: Union Pacific train YSt 65-24 arrived the Port of Stockton 0240am 9-25-12 and delivered to track # 5 Port of Stockton. At 0655am the YPS01-25 CCt switch crew was inspecting track  # 5 on the inbound mechanical and hazmat inspection of cars recivied in interchange and found the car had visible liquid on the side of the car and reported the car leaking to the CCT office. CCT office notiifed Dave Buccolo General manager and hazmat responder who advised office to have crew isolate car on track 808 CCT bad order track.  At 0721 Dave Buccolo arrived and locked and flagged bad order track and with Manager Jerry Martinez observed no liquid on the car but indications car may have leaked from manway cover. Manway was inspected and was found to have the top manway swing bolts at the 7 o'clock 9 0'clock and 11 o'clock locations on the manway loose to the touch and not hand tight. 7 o'clock swing bolt is seal bolt and is at manway handle. Manaway inspected and all three bolts were tightened down to proper torque spec.  Auxilluary fittings were also inspected as was bottom outlet valve and bottom outlet cap and there were no other exceptions taken. Car ok to move to consignee Buckeye Terminals at 0845. Three loose manway bolts were cause of the leak. shipper has been contacted as of 1030 hrs 9025-12
column169: Contacted shipper and advised them of the defect on this car and to please handle with the loadout crew to use proper STAR pattern when securing the manway on car and to double check every bolt for proper torque spec.  Contact at Green Plains Les Glinsmann  Plant manager phone 308-496-4800.  Recomend UP hazmat manager make trip to plant to observe loading and counsel the loaders and plant personal on proper loading and securment of hazmat shipments.

column168: A BNSF mechanical car inspector in the railyard reported a strong odor emanating from an area where a group of railcars were standing on the yard track. BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responders were notified and inspected the area for the odor source. Responders found tank car UTLX 68456 as the odor source. The manway cover was found secure along with other valves and their fittings. The manway cover was opened to inspect the condition of the manway gasket. The manway gasket was found deteriorated and cut in several locations which negated a good closure seal. A new manway gasket was installed and the manway was closed and properly secured. Afterwards, no further odor was detectable. Securement was completed by 1145 hrs. PDT, 9/18/2012. New seals BNSF 06157583 applied to valve housing cover and BNSF 06157589 at the manway closure.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: On 9/6/2012, a Kinder Morgan employee at the Chattanooga TRANSFLO terminal was preparing to start a transfer of 70% hydrogen peroxide from railcar to trailer via a peroxide transfer pump. Trailers were moved within the terminal by a 3rd party motor carrier. In this event, the motor carrier (Trimac) dropped the empty trailer to be loaded beside the wrong railcar. The employee began to hook the loading hoses from the peroxide pump to the trailer. During a verification the terminal manager recognized that the dropped trailer had been dropped beside the wrong railcar. The terminal manager radioed for the in-house third party jockey driver to return to the trailer and move the trailer to the correct railcar position. The driver immediately came back and backed his truck into the dropped trailer and re-connected. The terminal manager observed this and then told the driver not to move the truck until all loading connections had been removed from the trailer. After a few minutes the motor carrier driver ignored that instruction and began to pull away. The loading hose was still connected to the transfer pump. The hose was ripped out of the pump and approximately 1 gallon of hydrogen peroxide (70%) was released onto the ground. The pump was not running so only a residual amount of hydrogen peroxide was in the pump. The release was immediately cleaned up and repairs had to be made to the loading hoses and there was some damage to the transfer pump.
column169: DIRECT CAUSES:   1.Operating equipment without authority- The Trimac motor carrier driver was advised not to hook to the trailer until it was broken down.   2.Failure to communicate/coordinate  3.Failure to identify risks    ROOT CAUSES:   1.Misunderstood directions  2.Lack of situational awareness- Driver was not aware of the placement of the Loader on the trailer.   3.Inadequate development of standard- The use of a jack stand, or glad-hands, on a dropped trailer is required when loading commences but not called for during set up.      CORRECTIVE ACTIONS:   Training system evaluation and follow-up- The use of glad-hand locks will be required for all dropped trailers.  Procedures will be updated and affected personnel re-trained.

column168: A rolloff box arrived at the check in point of the intended waste disposal facility.  During a routine check, a small leak was detected from the rear of the box.  The truck was diverted to the containment area and a response crew was summoned.  After donning the appropirate personal protective equipment, it was found that the rear gasket had a small area which had deteriorated, allowing a small amount of liquid that had separated from the material to leak.  The material in the affected area was solidified and the absorbents used to clean up the spill were placed back into the box.  The shipment then proceeded to the intended waste disposal facility without further incident.
column169: The box was taken out of service when emptied for a new tailgate seal

column168: A shipment consisting of 7 flex bins of hazardous waste was loaded onto a van trailer destined to the intended waste disposal facility.  A few hours later, a small leak was observed underneath the trailer.  A response crew was notified, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and entered the trailer.  The sides of the flex bins had bulged out due to the weight of the material inside the inner plastic liner and, while loading, had apparently torn against the side of the trailer.  The bins were unloaded and repackaged into drums along with the abosrbent used to clean up the spilled material.  The damaged, soaked flex bins were also loaded into the drums. column168: On September 17, 2012, ERTS was contacted by Dana Companies to oversee environmental operations stemming from a motor oil and Aromatic 150 Fluid release at the Pilot truck stop in Dalton, GA. It was reported that a Dana Companies tanker truck was overturned resulting in a leak of product and motor oil. ERTS dispatched Marion Environmental to the site. Upon arrival, Marion personnel determined that the Aromatic 150 Fluid dripped into an onsite storm drain which did not lead to the onsite oil/water separator. Absorbents were applied to the impacted asphalt lot and the impacted storm drain. Contractor utilized an emergency unloading valve to trans load the Aromatic 150 Fluid material into a replacement tanker. Due to rains expected in the area, Marion dispatched a vac truck to pump the storm drain. All waste was containerized for transportation and disposal.
column169: This is considered to be a one time incident.

column168: Approximately 700 gallons of UN1760 Corrosive Liquid was released due to a tractor trailer rollover accident. The remaining product in the damaged totes was transferred into replacement containers and all of the waste was collected and containerized for disposal.

column168: On August 6, AFTAC shipped an excessed instrument containing approximately 0.84 microcuries Cs-137 and 3.4 nanocuries Eu-152 (these values are decayed from December 2004) to Pacific Northwest National Laboratory in Richland WA.  The instrument was packaged in a wooden box.  Neither the box nor the shipping paper indicated a hazardous material was present.  Package was carried by United Parcel Service and was delivered on August 13.  There was no damage to or release from the package.      Package was not opened at PNNL until September 10.  There was no marking on the external surface of the instrument.  There was no detectable dose rate on the external surface of the package nor on the external surface of the instrument.  Following partial disassembly of the instrument, radioactive material markings were noted within the instrument.  Strictly, the material was not in transportation at the time of discovery.  There was no release or impact to operations.

column168: Semi tractor and trailer experience a load-shift damaging freight.  During load shift, totes were punctured by pallets that were used as dividers. The pallets splintered, puncturing both totes, releasing ~550 gallons of material.  Release was ongoing for ~2 hours prior to fire department's arrival.  Local fire department contained release and prevented migration.  Hazmat crew recovered material and impacted soil for disposal over a course of 3 days after release was contained.
column169: Implement better blocking and bracing techniques.  Provide additional training for dock workers to better prepare for loading and securement.

column168: During a routine load and tire check In Smithton PA, the driver noticed liquid material coming from inside the trailer under the rear door. The driver placed absorbent pads along the bottom of the door and called his supervisor. A response crew was summoned. Upon arrival, they donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and entered the trailer. It was found that one drum was leaking through leaking from the lower body. A suitable salvage drum was used for repackaging of the leaking drum and all of the absorbent material used to contain and clean the spill. The truck was then secured and released to the intended waste disposal facility.
column169: At the time the driver accepted the container for transportation, no evidence of leaking was observed. The driver and packaging team, however, were re-instructed to conduct a thorough inspection of each container before shipping and acceptance for transportation;if any evidence of a reduction in structural integrity is found to take appropriate action to either place the container into a suitable salvage drum or re containerize before transportation is initiated.

On 09/17/2012 at 1401 hours, personnel in the Willard Yard, Willard, OH, discovered TLEX 1064, a loaded tank car of Alcohols N.O.S., leaking from the bottom of the rail car. The car was isolated and the shipper DIDION Ethanol LLC was notified thru CHEMTREC # 2012-09-15-00090. SWS Environmental Services, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found that the bottom outlet cap was loose and the valve was in the closed and locked position. The response team tighten the cap and the leak stopped. The issue was identified and the problem was relayed to the shipper representative Mr. Jim Lenz, 606 770 5093 of DIDION Ethanol LLC. The shipper contacted the FRA and has requested an OTMA to get the car to destination and be off loaded. Once the car is empty the shipper will request another OTMA from the FRA to have the car be sent to a repair shop for final repairs.     This incident did require a special switch move.     A 7.1 will be required for this incident    NARRI:  5 (3+3) X (2+0) = 60   Cause Code: 149 /5

On 09/13/12 at approximately 1430 hours, personnel in the CSXT Cumberland, MD yard  discovered UTLX 202947, a loaded tank car of Fuel Oil, leaking from the top of the car around the manway. The car was isolated and the shipper, Transflo Terminal Services, was notified, CHEMTREC Report # 2012-09-13-00177. Specialized Professional Services (SPSI), a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found one of 8 loose manway cover bolts partially dislodged from the cover. Contractor personnel tightened the manway cover bolt and cleaned up the spilled material. The leak was secured and the car was released for transport.     This incident did not require a special switching move.    This incident does not require a 7.1.     NARRI 5(5+1+0)X(2+0)=60  Cause Code:  200

UPON OPENING PACKAGE THE BOTTLE INSIDE WAS SECURE WELL WITH PACKAGING INSIDE A PLASTIC BAG. THE PLASTIC BAG DID CONTAIN SOME LIQUID. UPON TAKING THE BOTTLE OUTSIDE THE PLASTIC BAG, I TESTED THE CAP FOR TIGHTNESS DUE TO NO OTHER OBVIOUS DEFECTS IN THE BOTTLE.  CAP APPEARED TIGHT. UPON TURNING OVER THE BOTTLE LIQUID SLOWLY LEAKED FROM UNDER THE CAP. RETESTED THE CAP FOR TIGHTNESS AND STILL APPEARED TIGHT. TURNED OVER THE BOTTLE AND IT LEAKED AGAIN. ONLY A DEFECTIVE CAP CAN EXPLAIN THE LEAK. PACKAGE WAS OTHERWISE VERY WELL SECURED AND PACKAGE MUST HAVE BEEN ON ITS SIDE AT ONE POINT TO HAVE LEAKED OUT OF THE PLASTIC BAG. PACKAGE CUSHIONING WAS USED AS WELL AS SEPARATE BUILD-UP TO PREVENT MOVING.

column168: September 29, 2012: At approximately 1040AM, while working in North Yard, engineer Yelder of CR crew FD05 reported, via radio, of some kind of mist originating on top of tank car GATX 60960, load, Hydrochloric Acid, solution.  CR Trainmaster A. Parker researched the billing on the cars on track 17 in the Class, then inspected the area to confirm Mr. Yelder's report.    Mr. Parker contacted CR's A. Richter, Risk Management to advise.  Mr. Richter contacted designated customer for the cars, PVS Chemicals, Detroit and spoke with Ms. B. Bania.  Ms. Bania had someone from the plant inspect the cars on this track, destined for the Detroit, MI location and found tank car GATX 63215, load Hydrochloric Acid, solution, with a ruptured (as designed) 165 pound safety vent disc.    PVS representative changed out the disc in kind, wiped the immediate area of the fittings of moisture and the car was okayed to be forwarded for transportation to the original customer.  Car loaded originally by Momentive, Inc., Norco, LA.

column168: THE TRACTOR AND TRAILER WERE TRAVELING SOUTHBOUND ON COUNTY ROAD A APPROACHING 7765 COUNTY ROAD A. THE VEHICLE SLOWLY BEGAN DRIFTING OFF THE ROADWAY ONTO THE SHOULDER AND INTO THE DITCH. THE VEHICLE'S BRAKES WERE APPLIED AND THE DRIVER ATTEMPTED TURNING TO THE LEFT TO GET OUT OF THE DITCH AS THE TRACTOR AND TRAILER BEGAN TO TURN SIDEWAYS IN THE ROADWAY. THE TRAILER CONTINUED ALONG THE WEST DITCH OF COUNTY ROAD A UNTIL STRIKING THE TALL DITCH BANK OF 7743 COUNTY ROAD A. THIS CAUSE THE TRAILER TO OVERTURN PULLING THE TRACTOR WITH AND CAUSING IT TO OVERTURN. THE TRACTOR AND TRAILER CROSSED OVER THE DRIVEWAY AT 7743 COUNTY ROAD A ROLLING AGAIN AND COMING TO A REST ON THE SOUTH SIDE OF THE DRIVEWAY. THE TRUCK WAS FACING SOUTH EAST LAYING ON THE DRIVER'S SIDE OF THE TRACTOR AND TRAILER. THE TRAILER WAS CARRYING APPROXIMATELY 5,000 GALLONS OF GAS AND 3,000 GALLONS OF #2 FUEL OIL. THERE WAS A MINOR LEAK FROM THE CAP OF THE TANK THAT WAS CONTAINED BY USING ABSORBENT MATERIALS, LESS THAN 15 GALLONS WAS LEAKED. ONCE THE TANKER WAS UP RIGHTED AND STABLIZED, THE LEAK STOPPED AND REI CIVIL ENVIRONMENTAL ENGINEERING AND SURVEYING PERFORMED ADDITIONAL SOIL CLEAN UP. THE DURATION OF THE START OF THE ACCIDENT CLEANUP WAS ABOUT 10 HOURS.

column168: A shipment of 250 gallon totes was on the dock at the intermediate truck transfer facility awaiting loading into a trailer destined for the intended waste disposal facility when it was noticed one of them had a small pinhole leak.  A response crew was notified, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and cleaned up the spilled material with a suitable absorbent material.  The contents of the affected tote were repacked into another tote along with the material used to cleanup the spill.  The shipment was then loaded into a trailer destined for the intended waste disposal facility without further incident.  The spill was called in to IEMA who assigned incident number H2012-1036.

column168: The shipment was offered under a vessel sharing agreement to Hapag-Lloyd Container Line as non hazrdous material by NYK Linke, on behalf of their shipper, for transport on the Hapag-Lloyd container vessel Yorktown Express from Savannah, Georgia to Bremerhaven, Germany.    NYK advised Hapag-Lloyd after vessel had sailed from Savannah that the following was loaded in the container:    UN1760, Corrosive Liquid, NOS (Contains <10% Hydrochloric acid), Class 3, PG III  UN1263, Paint Related Material, Class 3, PG III, FP 27C    The shipping papers that accompanied the container did not indicate the presence of hazardous materials, and the container was not placarded/marked.    NYK/Shipper subsequently provided corrected hazardous material shipping papers to Hapag-Lloyd.    Hapag-Lloyd Advised the Master of the vessel of the undeclared hazardous materials onboard.

column168: On 09/26/2012, at 2055 hours, personnel in the CSXT Montgomery Terminal discovered NATX 252560, a loaded tank car of Xylenes, leaking from the manway area. The car was isolated and the shipper, Chevron Phillips Chemical Company, local fire department, Alabama EMA, NRC, and Chemtrec (report # 2012-09-26-00260) were notified. EPS of Vermont, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the gasket was missing from the manway. The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to shipper representative, Vicente Santa Cruz, 832-458-4327. Contractor personnel installed a new gasket, resealed the manway and decontaminated the car. The leak was secured and the car was released for transport. column168: AIRGAS VEHICLE (1) WAS TRAVELLING EAST BOUND ON U50 AT APPROXIMATELY 60 MPH IN A CONSTRUCTION ZONE WHEN THE DRIVER ALLEGEDLY HAD HIS ATTENTION DISTRACTED. WHEN HE LOOKED BACK THE ROAD HE NOTICED TRAFFIC WAS STOPPED IN FRONT OF HIM. THE DRIVER APPLIED HIS BRAKES AND CLIPPED VEHICLE (2) AND TOOK HIS VEHICLE OFF THE ROAD FOR A SHORT AMOUNT OF TIME BUT RATHER THAN CONTINUING DOWN INTO THE DITCH, THE DRIVER BROUGHT THE VEHICLE BACK UP ONTO THE ROAD AND OVER-CORRECTED CAUSING THE VEHICLE TO TURN ONTO ITS PASSENGER SIDE. ONCE ON ITS SIDE, THE VEHICLE (1) SLID INTO VEHICLE (3), (4), (5), AND (6) VIA A CHAIN REACTION. LIQUID OXYGEN WAS LEAKING OUT OF A PUNCTURE ON THE TOP PASSENGER SIDE OF THE TANK. THE INNER VESSEL WAS PUNCTURED. ADDITIONALLY, LIQUID OXYGEN WAS LEAKING OUT OF THE MAN HOLE TOWARDS THE BACK OF THE VEHICLE AT THE CENTER, TOP OF THE TANK.    FUEL WAS COVERED WITH PEAT MOSS BY THE FIRE DEPARTMENT AND THE AREA WAS QUARANTINED TO REDUCE THE CHANCE OF CREATING A FIRE DUE TO THE LIQUID OXYGEN LEAK ONTO THE ASPHALT. THE LIQUID IN THE TANK WAS REMOVED THROUGH THE PLUMBING (WHICH WAS STILL INTACT) IN THE REAR OF THE VEHICLE INTO THE DITCH ON THE SIDE OF THE ROAD UNTIL THE LIQUID LEVEL WAS SUCH THAT NO FURTHER LIQUID COULD BE REMOVED.    THE VEHICLES WERE REMOVED FROM THE SCENE ONE BY ONE. ONCE ALL OTHER VEHICLES WERE REMOVED FROM THE SCENE, THE AIRGAS VEHICLE WAS TURNED RIGHT SIDE UP AND THE REST OF THE LIQUID OXYGEN WAS RELEASED INTO THE DITCH SO THAT IS COULD BE MOVED TO A SECURE LOCATION. WATER WAS USED TO DISPENSE AND DILUTE THE OXYGEN RELEASED.
column169: AIRGAS USA, LLC MID SOUTH REGION PROVIDED SEVERAL SAFETY TOPICS TO PREVENT THIS KIND OF ACCIDENT FROM OCCURRING IN THE FUTURE. THE FIRST WAS CONSTRUCTION ZONE AWARENESS TOPICS. THE SECOND WAS CELLULAR PHONE WHILE OPERATING CMV RETRAINING. THE THIRD WAS PHYSICAL AND MENTAL HEALTH AWARENESS TRAINING AND COMMUNICATION PROTOCOLS BETWEEN DRIVERS AND TERMINAL MANAGERS. OPERATING PROCEDURES AND PACKAGING WAS NOT A ROOT CAUSE IN THIS RELEASE.

column168: An ammonia odor was reported in the railyard. The local F.D. using air monitoring devices could not detect ammonia gases in the air at ground level around suspect tank cars. BNSF and contract responders continued to search for the odor source amongst the suspect tank cars. Residue tank car DGCX 1129 was found emanating vapors at the valve housing cover due to the A-end liquid and vapor valves not fully closed and these valves closure plugs not tool tight. The responders closed the A-end valves and tool tightened their closure plugs which eliminated the vapor release. Intact shipper seal 3636763 at the housing cover was replaced with seal WENCK2039.  During the process of moving/isolating suspect railcars in the railyard for detailed inspection to determine the odor source, a nearby BNSF employee reported exposure to ammonia vapors and was taken to a local hospital for examination and follow-up treatment.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: FURX 123023 was reported to be releasing diesel fuel from the top of the car. Inspection found approximately two gallons of fuel on the side of the tank car. Two of eight manway swing bolts were in the down position and four of the eight bolts were not tool tight, allowing product to be released from the manway nozzle. In addition, the air valve plug was not tool tight, the air and liquid valves were both left open, and one unloading fixture was left on the liquid valve. However, product was only released from the manway nozzle. The car was resecured and allowed to continue in transportation. No remediation was needed because none of the product reached the ground.
column169: Ensure cars are properly prepared for movement prior to being released.

column168: MAINTENANCE CONNECTED THE FACILITY'S UNLOADING LINE TO THE TANK CAR. WHEN THE OPERATOR OPENED THE TANK CAR'S VALVE ON THE UNLOADING LINE, VAPORS AND LIQUID STARTED SPRAYING OUT FROM THE FLANGE BETWEEN THE VALVE AND WELL LINE DUE TO THE PRESSURE IN THE TANK CAR. THE OPERATOR HAD NOT APPLIED ANY PRESSURE TO THE TANK CAR. THE CONTENTS WERE UNDER PRESSURE FROM AMBIENT WEATHER CONDITIONS. A MECHANIC WAS ABLE TO TIGHTEN THE 4 BOLTS IN THE FLANGE APPROXIMATELY ONE-QUARTER TURN EACH AND THE LEAK STOPPED. NOX FUMES WERE GENERATED WHEN THE ACID REACTED WITH WATER USED TO ASSIST THE MECHANIC IN ACCESSING THE BOLTS AND WHEN SOME OF THE ACID REACTED WITH GRAVEL AROUND THE TANK CAR. THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER WAS CALLED SINCE THE NOX RELEASE WAS DETERMINE TO BE AT LEAST 10 POUNDS.

column62: Human Error; Improper Preparation for Transportation
column168: Our Event 34921.    This trailer was pre-loaded by the shipper.  Our driver performs our standard pre-trip inspection before departing (including verifying closures are in place), and no anomolies were noted.  At the Consignee, our driver prepared the trailer for unloading and applied air pressure to convey product to the Consignee's storage tank.  At this point, he noticed product vapor venting from the blanked-off loading flange.  He depressurized the trailer and inspected the loading flange closure.  He noticed that two of the four bolts appeared to be overtightened, causing the flange to be slightly mis-aligned.      Our driver removed, inspected and reinstalled the flange-blank, replacing the two defective bolts.  Product residue on the side of the trailer was water rinsed to the Consignee's containment area.  Our driver completed unloading without further incident.
column169: This trailer is equipped with a secondary closure, which is a butterfly valve between the flange and the tank.  Inspection by our shop shows that the butterfly valve is fully operational, so it is presumed that the butterfly valve was not in the fully closed position during this incident.  We have added an item to our pre-trip inspection for this specific Shipper, which is to verify the butterfly valve is in the fully closed position.

column168: On September 29, 2012 at 1012 hours, personnel in the CSXT Selkirk Yard discovered APRX 6011, a loaded tank car of Argon, UN1951, venting continuously from the BL side cabinet. A CSXT HazMat Sentinel responded and found the PRD in the BL Side box to be venting continuously, the valve piping frozen over with a heavy coating of ice. The piping was de-iced and the PRD reset. At 1350 hours the tank car was moved to destination under verbal FRA movement approval #20120929R1V for unloading.    This incident did require a special switching move.    AAR 7.1 will be completed.    NARRI: 2x(3+1+0)x(5+0) = 40  Cause Code:  422

column168: CN switch crew reported vapors coming from the top of tank car RCRX 1097 during switching operations at the CN Mays Yard, Hanrahan, LA.  All appropriate departments notified, tank car isolated. CN's response team responded, upon closer inspection, vapors were observed coming from between the fill hole cover lid and the fill hole nozzle.  Liquid was observed on the pressure plate.  The bolts securing the fill hole cover were checked and were unable to be turned by hand.  I pipe wrench was used and several additional turns on each bolt were obtained. column168: Passenger baggage contained nail-care products including (4), 480-ml glass bottles of "Competition 3000 ECT Liquid (Ethyl Methacrylate). The proper shipping name is Consumer Commodity ORM-D, Class 9, ID8000. Strong odor was noticed during loading and it was tracked to a checked passenger item where one broken, bubble-wrapped 480-ml bottle was discovered. Passengers were removed from the aircraft to allow odor to dissipate. Spill was confined to passenger baggage, but additional bags were removed to allow odor to dissipate as a precaution. Passenger and crew did de-plane and flight was delayed, but delay was also due to unrelated mechanical issue.            Flight was delayed, but did depart that evening.Passenger was questioned and expressed remorse and embarrassment for having caused a problem.  He did not re-board the flight.

column168: Vehicle was N-B on IH35 main lanes.  Driver claims he swerved to right to avoid animal crossing roadway.  Vehicle ran off right side of roadway and rolled onto right side.  Vehicle came to rest on it's right side on the grassy median separating the mainlines from frontage road.    During rollover, a compartment manhole cover came loose to secondary clamp position.  Approximately 2900 gallons of gasoline flowed from the partially opened manhole cover. First responders clamped the manhole shut prior to evacuation of the product.  The remaining product was removed from the cargo tank.  The vehicle was righted and moved away to storage.  Environmental spill personnel were on scene and began remediation work immediately.  Contaminated soil was removed and replaced.  The environmental clean up efforts were completed within 36 hours.    During the product removal, northbound traffic was diverted to Toll 130.

column168: A Veolia employee observed a small liquid leak from a straight truck while it was parked at the Veolia facility located in Menomonee Falls, WI. Upon investigation, it was determined that the source of the leak was a 14 gallon fiber drum of labpack chemicals that included two - 4 liter containers of mercury acetate solution. When discovered both of the 4 liter inner containers were broken while in transit. The spilled liquid was immediately cleaned up and the absorbents were then placed into another container for proper disposal.
column169: This incident was reviewed with field service employees, emphasizing the need to ensure an appropriate amount of absorbent is added to each labpack container to both cushion the inner packagings and also in a sufficient amount enough to absorb the entire liquid contents.

column168: AN AUSTIN POWDER COMPANY (AUSTIN) TRUCK TRACTOR/TRAILER COMBINATION TRANSPORTING CLASS 1 EXPLOSIVES (AUSTIN VEHICLE), TRAVELING EASTBOUND ON US 90, APPROACHED AND STOPPED AT A WELL-MARKED RAILROAD GRADE CROSSING AS REQUIRED BY 49 CFR 392.10. AS THE AUSTIN VEHICLE STOPPED, ANOTHER COMMERCIAL MOTOR VEHICLE TOWING A TRAILER (OTHER VEHICLE), TRAVELING IN THE SAME DIRECTION, BUT BEHIND THE AUSTIN VEHICLE, COLLIDED INTO THE RIGHT REAR OF THE AUSTIN VEHICLE. THE AUSTIN DRIVER STATED THAT HE FELT THE COLLISION, AND MOVED THE AUSTIN VEHICLE FORWARD ACROSS THE RAILROAD TRACKS TO A SAFER POSITION ON THE RIGHT SHOULD WHERE HE PARKED IT. UPON EXISTING THE AUSTIN VEHICLE, HE IMMEDIATELY ASSESSED THE SCENE AND CALL 911, AND THEN CONTACTED AUSTIN FOR ASSISTANCE. AS A RESULT OF THE IMPACT, THE DRIVER OF THE OTHER VEHICLE WAS FATALITY INJURED. THE AUSTIN DRIVER WAS NOT INJURED. THERE WAS NO RELEASE OF ANY HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. THERE WERE NO WITNESSES TO THIS ACCIDENT, OTHER THAN THE AUSTIN DRIVER. AUSTIN REPORTED THE ACCIDENT TO THE NRC. THE STATE POLICE CLOSED THE EASTBOUND SIDE OF US 90 FOR ABOUT 4 HOURS BECAUSE OF AMOUNT OF DEBRIS ON THE ROADWAY CAUSED BY THE WRECKAGE OF OTHER VEHICLE, AS WELL AS THE INVESTIGATION CONDUCTED BY THEM DUE TO THE FATALITY. AFTER RELEASING TRAFFIC FLOW ON EASTBOUND SIDE OF US 90, THE STATE POLICE ORDERED THE AUSTIN DRIVER TO MOVE AUSTIN VEHICLE TO A NEARBY REST STOP WHERE A HAZMAT TEAM OVERSAW THE TRANSFER OF ALL CARGO TO ANOTHER VEHICLE, OPERATED BY ANOTHER DRIVER, THAT WAS SUBSEQUENTLY DRIVEN TO IT INTENDED DESTINATION, JUST A FEW MILES AWAY. AUSTIN SENT A THIRD-PARTY, INDEPENDENT CRASH SPECIALIST TO THE ACCIDENT, WHO ARRIVED LATER IN THE DAY. HE REVIEWED THE ACCIDENT SCENE, SPOKE WITH THE STATE POLICE, INTERVIEWED THE AUSTIN DRIVER, AND INSPECTED THE AUSTIN VEHICLE. THE STATE POLICE INDICATED THAT THE OTHER CARRIER'S DRIVER CAUSED THE ACCIDENT. THE AUSTIN CRASH SPECIALIST FINDINGS AND CONCLUSIONS CLEARLY INDICATE THAT THE OTHEER DRIVER CAUSED THE ACCIDENT. AS SUCH, THIS ACCIDENT SHOULD BE CONSIDERED AS "NON-PREVENTABLE" FOR AUSTIN BASED ON THE DEFINITION OF "PREVENTABLE" IN 49 CFR 385.3.
column169: IN ACCORDANCE WITH 49 CFR 392.10, AND LOUISIANA 32:173.1, THE AUSTIN VEHICLE WAS REQUIRED TO STOP AT THIS PARTICULAR RAILROAD GRADE CROSSING. THE AUSTIN DRIVER WAS FAMILIAR WITH THE ROUTE HE WAS TRAVELING AND FULLY ANTICIPATED STOPPING AT THE RAILROAD GRADE CROSSING. FOR SOME UNKNOWN REASON, THE OTHER DRIVER FAILED TO PERCEIVE AND REACT TO THE AUSTIN VEHICLE STOPPING AT THE RAILROAD CROSSING. AUSTIN WOULD SUGGEST THAT THIS RAILROAD GRADE CROSSING BE CONSIDERED FOR A SAFETY RISK ANALYSIS TO DETERMINE MEASURES TO PREVENT FUTURE ACCIDENTS FOR THREE REASONS: (1) THIS CROSSING IS ONLY A SPUR THAT IT NOT OFTEN USED, (2) THE POSTED SPEED LIMIIT OF US 90 IN THE VICINITY OF THIS CROSSING IS 65 MPH AND (3) OTHER ACCIDENTS HAVE OCCURRED AT THIS CROSSING.

THE DRIVER OF THE OTHER VEHICLE RAN A RED LIGHT AND COLLIDED WITH THE FRONT OF OUR TRUCK. UNFORTUNATELY, THE DRIVER OF THE CAR WAS FATALLY WOUNDED AND OUR DRIVER WAS ABLE TO CRAWL OUT OF THE CAB AFTER IT OVERTURNED. APPROXIMATELY 9,000 GALLONS OF GASOLINE SPILLED AND IGNITED.

column168: The delivery truck was struck in the left rear axle by an oncomming car that crossed over the yellow line.  The impact broke the rear suspension and allowed the driveshaft to drop from the transmission.  The truck then laid over in it's left side and slid down the highway.  Damage occurred to the rear deck of the delivery truck which caused product release.  Sparks from sliding down the road ignited the product.  Fire and rescue personnel responded to the scene.  Our company representative was dispatched immediately to the scene.  Water streams were applied to the truck by the fire department.  Hazmat personnel closed all of the valves at the rear of the truck stopping the product release.  Product release occurred for approximately 6 hours.  All product released was consumed in the resulting fire.
column169: This incident was caused by another driver crossing the yellow line and striking our vehicle.  Little can be done to prevent the neglegence of others.  All safeties operated as designed.  I have no suggestions for improvement.

column168: Tank car RCRX 2479(R/ HYDROCHLORIC ACID) was observed venting during switching operations at the CN Fulton Yard, Fulton, KY. The railcar was isolated and all appropriate departments notified. Shipper notified consignee / car owner Reagent Chemical who's response contractor responded noting vapors coming from the blind flange, T-assembly on the vapor line. All bolts securing the blind flange were found less than tool tight allowing product vapors to escape. The bolts were tightened and the venting stopped, car released to destination.

column168: (A) A FRA Inspector inspecting railcars in the railyard reported finding residue tank cars that were recently unloaded emanating an audible hiss (vapor release) from their manway closures. No liquid product release was reported. The nearby unloader of these tank cars (Kinder Morgan) was notified and sent a responder to secure the manway closures. The responder reported that all manway securement bolts were properly tool tightened on ADMX 30728 which eliminated any further vapor release from the manway closure. (B)A FRA Inspector inspecting railcars in the railyard reported finding residue tank cars that were recently unloaded emanating an audible hiss (vapor release) from their manway closures. No liquid product release was reported. The nearby unloader of these tank cars (Kinder Morgan) was notified and sent a responder to secure the manway closures. The responder reported that all manway securement bolts were properly tool tightened on TILX 317988 which eliminated any further vapor release from the manway closure. (C) A FRA Inspector inspecting railcars in the railyard reported finding residue tank cars that were recently unloaded emanating an audible hiss (vapor release) from their manway closures. No liquid product release was reported. The nearby unloader of these tank cars (Kinder Morgan) was notified and sent a responder to secure the manway closures. The responder reported that all manway securement bolts were properly tool tightened on ADMX 30454 which eliminated any further vapor release from the manway closure. (D) A FRA Inspector inspecting railcars in the railyard reported finding residue tank cars that were recently unloaded emanating an audible hiss (vapor release) from their manway closures. No liquid product release was reported. The nearby unloader of these tank cars (Kinder Morgan) was notified and sent a responder to secure the manway closures The responder reported that the misaligned/damaged manway gasket was replaced on ADMX 30929 and all manway securement bolts properly tool tightened which eliminated any further vapor release from the manway closure.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: VEHICLE WAS NORTHBOUND AT I-55 NORTHBOUND SCALE AT BOLINGBROOK, IL. A DRIP WAS FOUND AT THE PRODUCT VALVE OF THE TRAILER. SPILL KIT BUCKET WAS DEPLOYED IMMEDIATELY BY THE DRIVER. THERE WAS NO PRODUCT ON THE GROUND. UPON CARRIER INTIATIVE, A SECOND TRAILER WAS SENT IMMEDIATELY TO THE SCALE TO TRANSFER THE PRODUCT. LESS THAN HALF A PINT OF PRODUCT DRIPPED INTO THE BUCKET WHILE THE PRODUCT WAS BEING TRANSFERRED. THE SCALE HOUSE WAS SHUT DOWN DURING THE TRANSFER OF PRODUCT FOR APPROXIMATELY 1.5 HOURS. THE TRAVELED PORTION OF THE HIGHWAY WAS UNAFFECTED.  UPON RETURN OF THE TANKER TO THE TERMINAL AND FURTHER INSPECTION, THE EXTERNAL SUMP GASKET, THROUGH NORMAL USAGE, BECAME DEFECTIVE AND CAUSED MINOR SEEPAGE. THIS WOULD BE DETECTED ONLY THROUGH PRESSURE TESTING AND NOT BY A DRIVER/MECHANIC IN NORMAL VEHICLE INSPECTIONS.PLEASE FIND ATTACHED OUR LATEST BRENNER PRESSURE TEST PAPERWORK DATED 05/27/2011.
column169: TRAILER WAS TAKEN BACK TO MANUFACTURER BRENNER, MAUSTON, WI, FOR COMPLETE VIKP INSPECTIONS AND NECESSARY REPAIRS.

column168: A 55-gallon drum of the referenced product appeared to have been punctured from a nail on the pallet inside of a Landstar Ranger tractor trailer.  ERTS was contacted to oversee environmental operations.  ERTS dispatched Hazchem which responded to the site and performed the necessary cleanup activities.

Tankcar FMLX 200035, load of hydrogen peroxide, was upright off the tracks with damage to the B/R head and tank shell.  This car released product from the bottom of the four-bolt fill port on the liquid eduction plumbing at the top of the car.  According to Environmental Management, ER Contractor,  all four bolts were found loose on the fill port as a result of  derailment forces, allowing an estimated 50-100 gallons of product to be released.  All four bolts were tightened and local responders neutralized the material with water, eliminating the hazard.
column169: Continue routine inspection's of fittings and securements upon unloading and loading procedures.

column168: Tankcar FMLX 200035, load of hydrogen peroxide, was upright off the tracks with damage to the B/R head and tank shell.  This car released product from the bottom of the four-bolt fill port on the liquid eduction plumbing at the top of the car.  According to Environmental Management, ER Contractor,  all four bolts were found loose on the fill port as a result of  derailment forces, allowing an estimated 50-100 gallons of product to be released.  All four bolts were tightened and local responders neutralized the material with water, eliminating the hazard.
column169: Continue routine inspection's of fittings and securements upon unloading and loading procedures.

Tank car PROX 69427 on the BNSF facility repair track was reported leaking product from the top fitting area when the A-end of this tank car was being raised to accommodate required repairs. All activity was ceased. Investigation of the leak source revealed that the frangible disc in the safety vent had ruptured possibly sometime prior to the initiation of the repair activity. The 165 psi frangible disc was replaced in kind. All other valves and fittings were found secure. The small amount of product that trickled down the exterior tank shell was cleaned. No product impacted the ground.

A 53-foot Heritage Transport trailer was parked on the lot of Heritage Environmental Services in Kansas City, MO.  When the driver hooked up his tractor he noticed a small drip coming from the nose of the trailer onto his rear wheel fender.  He immediately notified the Facility Manager and, upon investigation, the leaking container was discovered and overpacked.  A pinhole-sized opening on the bottom of a 55-gallon steel, closed-top container was found to be the source of the leak.  Floor-dry and rags were used to clean up the small amount of liquid inside the trailer, the fender and asphalt parking lot.  This material was collected and placed inside an 85-gallon poly overpack along with the leaking 55-gallon metal drum.  Approximately twenty minutes elapsed between the discovery of the leak and the final clean-up of this container.  While overpacking this leaking container, Heritage personnel noticed a second container began leaking.  Since a second container began leaking, the trailer was pulled up to the dock of Heritage Environmental Services' Treatment, Storage and Disposal Facility where all containers were unloaded.  During the process of unloading the trailer and overpacking the second leaking container, three additional containers began to leak.  Therefore, those containers were also overpacked along with three remaining containers of the same waste stream that were not leaking.  A total of eight containers were overpacked as a precautionary measure.  The resources required to complete these actions took approximately six hours utilizing four Heritage personnel.
column169: Heritage contacted the offerer to discuss the use of alternative packaging for this waste stream in the future to prevent recurrence.

column62: Valve Open; Missing Component or Device
column168: CHEMTREC notified BNSF that a concerned citizen reported an entrained tank car leaking. The suspect BNSF train was stopped on main track for BNSF mechanical responders to inspect. The responders reported finding entrained tank car UTLX 213351 with its bottom outlet closure cap (BOC) not applied and hanging on its securement chain. Responders applied the BOC and properly tool tightened it. Also, the bottom outlet valve's (BOV) operating handle was not pinned in its closed position and no shipper seals were observed. The unpinned operating handle allowed vibration to slightly open the BOV. The BOV operating handle was securely pinned in its closed position. After the BOV/BOC securement was completed, no further product drips were evident. Minor ground spillage observed was evaporating.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: Arriving inbound container OOLU 854367 was reported leaking an unknown substance and it was deemed safe to move to the facility's containment area for detailed interior inspection, leak source determination and remediation. Contract responders reported the leak source was one top stacked palletized 55 gallon drum that sustained a 3 inch abrasion cut below its lower rolling hoop from rubbing against an adjacent palletized unit. Absence of void fillers or buffering materials between palletized units was noted.  Also noted was that these palletized drums were stacked atop a smaller wooden crate which did not provide a stable base and allowed additional movement of the stacked palletized units. The compromised drum was overpacked; and interior and exterior spillage was cleaned.
column169: Ensure shipper follows approved loading arrangements that include usage of appropriate filler material to prevent undesired lading to lading contact; and palletized lading is properly weight distributed and resting on a stable base.

column168: During railcar inspections of an outbound track in the railyard, tank car DBUX 303243 was reported dripping product from its bottom outlet valve (BOV). DBUX 303243 was cordoned off awaiting a detailed inspection. A contract responder's inspection of DBUX 303243 determined the product was dripping from the valve stem of the closed bottom operated BOV. The responder could not access the valve stem for repairs/securement as a steel plate was welded over the valve stem access hole in the adjacent skid plate. DBUX 303243 was carefully moved to an isolated location in the railyard for product transfer. All lading within DBUX 303243 was transferred without further incident into another suitable tank car by 1945 hrs. CDT, 9/29/2012.  Afterwards, the product drip from DBUX 303243's BOV ceased. Spillage captured in a catch receptacle evaporated and no ground impact was observed. DBUX 303243 is currently awaiting FRA OTMA authorization for movement to a qualified repair facility.
column169: No additional comments.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column168: A BNSF crewed train operating on the UPRR was alerted that an entrained tank car was hissing and emanating a chlorine odor. Inspection by UPRR and local F.D. responders revealed entrained residue tank car TILX 600722 was the odor source. Further inspection resulted in the 375 psi Midland pressure relief valve (PRV) being identified as the escaping vapor source. Responders successfully applied a chlorine capping kit appliance over the failed PRV ending the vapor emissions into the atmosphere. TILX 600722 was set-out of the train and isolated at a nearby siding. The residue chlorine within TILX 600722 was transferred into trucks and chlorine vapors sparged through sodium hydroxide. The responders depressurized TILX 600722 and replaced the failed PRV in kind. OTMA FRA-12090842 was received to transport TILX 600722 to a qualified repair facility for leakproofness testing of the replacement PRV.

ON SEPTEMBER 13TH, ONE OF OUR DRIVERS WAS HAULING A LOAD OF TERGITOL (SOAP) IN A TANKER TRAILER AND WAS IN ROUTE TO HIS DELIVERY. WHILE HE WAS IN TRANSIT HE NOTICED THAT THERE WAS PRODUCT LEAKING DOWN THE SIDE OF HIS TRAILER. THE DRIVER WENT ON TOP OF THE TRAILER AND DISCOVERED THAT ONE OF THE CLEAN OUT CAPS HAD COME LOOSE. THE DRIVER RE-APPLIED THE CLEAN OUT CAP ON THE TRAILER WHICH TOOK CARE OF THE PROBLEM. WE CALLED IN SWS ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES TO CLEAN UP THE PRODUCT THAT LEAKED OFF THE TRAILER AND ONTO THE GROUND. IT IS ESTIMATED THAT APPROXIMATELY 5 GALLONS OF PRODUCT WAS RELEASED FROM THE TRAILER. THE CLEAN-UP CREW SPREAD SPEEDY DRY ON THE GROUND AND CLEANED UP THE AFFECTED AREA.    UPON INVESTIGATING THIS INCIDENT, IT HAS BEEN DETERMINED THAT THIS COULD HAVE BEEN AVOIDED HAD THE DRIVER DONE A PROPER PRE-TRIP INSPECTION AND INSPECTED THE CLEAN OUT CAP THAT IS ON TOP OF THE TRAILER. IT IS THE DRIVERS RESPONSIBILITY TO MAKE SURE THAT THE CLEAN OUT CAP HAS A GASKET IN PLACE AND IT IS NOT CROSS-THREADED.
column169: IMMEDIATELY AFTER THE INCIDENT THE DRIVER WAS BOUGHT INTO THE OFFICE AND WE REVIEWED THE INCIDENT WITH HIM. THE DRIVER WENT THROUGH HANDS ON REFRESHER TRAINING ON HOW TO INSPECT THE CLEAN OUT CAPS ON A TRAILER. WE DOCUMENTED THIS INCIDENT IN THE DRIVERS FILE AND ISSUED HIM A SUSPENSION DAY. ADDITIONALLY WE SENT OUT A MEMO TO THE FLEET INFORMING THEM OF THIS INCIDENT AND REMINDED THEM TO FOLLOW THE COMPANY POLICY FOR CHECKING THE CLEAN OUT CAPS ON THE TRAILER. WE WILL ALSO DISCUSS THIS EVENT AT OUR NEXT SAFETY MEETING.

column168: DRIVER WAS EASTBOUND ON HIGHWAY 2 APPROACHING OLD CHENEY ROAD IN LINCOLN, NE AT 11:30 AM CDT. WHEN THE LIGHT TURNED YELLOW, HE INITALLY THOUGHT HE COULD MAKE IT THROUGH BUT THEN SAW CARS START TURNING IN FRONT OF HIM, SO HE HAD TO MAKE A HARD BRAKE. THE CONTAINERS ON THE FLATBED WERE HELD DOWN WITH APPROXIMATELY 4 INCH SYNTHETIC STRAPS WHICH ALL APPEARED TO HAVE BEEN CUT BY THE EDGE OF THE CONTAINERS. THE TWO CONTAINERS SLID FORWARD AND ONE OF THE CONTAINERS SLID OFF THE FLATBED TRAILER INTO THE BACK OF THE TRACTOR AND IMPACTED APPROXIMATELY ONE FOOT INTO THE BACK OF THE SLEEPER CAB. THE VEHICLE WAS STOPPED IN THE MIDDLE OF THE INTERSECTION OF OLD CHENEY ROAD AND HIGHWAY 2. AFTER LFR AND HEALTH DEPARTMENT DETERMINED THE AREA WAS SAFE AND THE CONTAINERS WERE NOT BREACHED, A CRANE WAS CALLED IN TO PICK THE CONTAINERS AND PLACED THEM BACK ON THE TRAILER SO THE TRACTOR AND TRAILER COULD BE TOWED AWAY.    THE PACKAGES RECEIVED VERY MINOR DAMAGE TO THE SUB-FRAME, WAS NOT BREACHED AND THERE WAS NO RELEASE.
column169: WE HAVE TAKEN SEVERAL STEPS TO IMPROVE OUR LOAD SECUREMENT FOR THESE PACKAGES:    1. WE ARE REQUIRING THE SHIPPER TO PLACE FRICTION MATS BETWEEN THE TRAILER DECK AND THE BOTTOM OF THE PACKAGE.    2. WE ARE REQUIRING OUR DRIVERS TO USE EDGE PROTECTORS UNDER THE 4" SYNTHETIC STRAPS.    3. WE HAVE FABRICATED 8" ALUMINUM CHANNEL BRACING PLACED AT THE FRONT OF THE PACKAGE TO PREVENT FORWARD MOVEMENT.    4. ON HEAVIER BOXES (OVER 10,000 LBS) WE ARE REQUIRING DRIVERS TO ADD AN ADDITIONAL CHAIN THROUGH THE FORKLIFT POCKET.

column168: Spill occurred during off-loading process from tank wagon (MC-306 trailer) to above ground storage tank (AST) (16,000 gallon capacity).  AST overflowed when driver of vehicle failed to recognize that product would not fit as ordered and misinterpreted the size of the tank.  Product escaped from the vent pipe on top of the tank, flowed down the side onto a cement pad then into the soil.  After the second day a small quantity was found in a tributary of the Ohio River in which boom had been previously placed from a previous spill that had occurred earlier in the year. (Previous spill not as a result of actions of Penn Tank Lines.)  The product that entered the river appears to have followed the course or length of a pipe that had been used over 20 years (estimated time) ago to off-load barges from the tributary and was not in use. There was no failure of packaging.
column169: Better training of drivers and label AST's with capacity of tank. Facility had inadequate spill protection.

column168: Spill discovered by hostler operator at approximately 11:30 pm on Sunday night.  Spill reported to TEMA at 12:02 am Monday morning.  The spill occurred in trailer 313-0466, which was staged on a concrete pad located approxicmatley 150-200 fee east of Door #128.  The trailer had been dropped at the staging location on the Con-way yard after arriving from the shipper.  The trailer was not scheduled for unloading at the terminal.  Four 30-gallon containers of Endothalll were on the trailer.  An employee discovered the material dripping from the trailer onto the concrete pad and nearby asphalt.   The service center notified Emergency Response & Training Solutions to assist in the coordination of the clean up by outside vendor.  ERTS dispatched B&P Enterprises to the scene for initial response and remediation activities.  B&P discovered slit in top of drum.  ERTS notified TEMA (1983) and NRC.

column168: DURING A HEAVY RAIN EVENT, JUST AFTER 3:00PM CENTRAL TIME ON SEPTEMBER 17, 2012, GOC WAS OFF-LOADING DYED DIESEL FUEL #2 INTO A 14,600 GALLON AVE GROUND STORAGE TANK WHEN THE TANK WAS ACCIDENTALLY RELEASED BY 401 GALLONS. THE OVERFILLED FUEL WAS PROMPTLY TRANSPORTED BY RAINWATER ALONG A DRAINAGE DITCH BEFORE SOME OF IT DISCHARGED INTO A WESTWARD FLOWING CREEK THE SPILL WAS NOT DISCOVERED UNTIL THE NEXT DAY WHEN GOC CHECKED THE TANK FITTING NUMBERS. GOC REPORTED THE SPILL TO THE MDEQ AND ARRANGED FOR THE CREEK TO BE INSPECTED. SPILLED FUEL WAS MINIZED TO THE CREEK WEST AND TO JUST BEYOND SOUTH LONGJUSTICE STREET. DOMBS AND PADS WERE PLACED AT SCENE LOCKING IN THE CREEK. ON SEPTEMBER 19, 2012, ADDITIONAL FUEL WAS VACUMMED FROM THE CREEK. THE CREEK WAS MONITORED FOR THE NEXT SEVERAL WEEKS AND BOOMS LEFT CHARTED WITH SO NEW FUEL OR SUBSTAIN WAS OBSERVED AFTER A HEAVY RAIN EVENT. A GEOLOGIST ASSED THE EXTEND OF CONTAMINATED SOIL AT THE GOC BULK PLANT AND OVERSAW EXCAVATION OF CONTAIMINATED SOIL ON SEPTEMBER 27, 2012, WHEN 11.53 PART OF SOIL WAS TRANSPORTED OFF SITE FOR DISPOSAL. THE GEOLOGIST EXAMINED CONTAMINATED SOIL SAMPLES ALONG THE EXCAVATION WHICH ALL TESTED BELOW STANDARD A REPORT WAS SUBMITTED TO THE MDEQ.
column169: AN INVESTIGATION IDENTIFIED THAT THE TANK OVERFILL WAS DUE TO HUMAN ERROR. GOC PERSONNEL WERE INSTRUCTED ABOUT AVOIDING SIMILAR ERROS IN THE FUTURE. ADDITIONALLY, A NEW LARGE GARTHER BERM WAS CONSTRUCTED AROUND GOC'S ABOVE GROUND TANKS FOR SPILL CONTAINMENT. GOC PERSONNEL WERE ALSO INSTRUCTED TO MEASURE THE TANK WITH ESTIMATING STICKS BOTH BEFORE AND AFTER UNLOADING PRODUCT INTO IT, EVEN IF IT IS RAINING. GOC PERSONNEL WERE ALSO INSTRUCTED TO CONVERT THE MEASURING STICK MEASUREMENT (IN INCHES) TO GALLONS AND ADD THE PLANNED DELIVERY GALLON VOLUME TO DETERMINE IF THE TANK WILL HOLD THE PLANNED DELIVERY VOLUME, BEFORE INITIATING THE UNLOADING PROCEDURE.

NO WATERWAYS WERE IMPACTED BY THE SPILL. THE LEAK LASTED LESS THAN ONE HOUR. WCEC HIRED A CONTRACTOR TO CLEAN UP THE CONTAMINATED SOIL ON A LATER DATE AFTER ALL THE CORRECT PERMITS WERE COMPLETED.

column168: A BULK TRANSFER TRAILER OF SULFURIC ACID WAS LOADED AT THE NYRSTAR FACILITY IN CLARKSVILLE, TENNESSEE BY NYRSTAR PERSONNEL. AFTER LOADING, PALM FREIGHT'S DRIVER WEIGHED THE TANKER ON-SITE, CONDUCTED PRE-TRIP CHECKS, AND EXITED THE FACILITY. AT 5:43 P.M., A NYRSTAR REPRESENTATIVE SENT AN EMAIL TO THE CONSIGNEE'S PLANT MANAGER INDICATING THAT A TANKER OF THE CONSIGNEE'S PRODUCT LEAVING THEIR FACILITY WAS LEAKING ACID. THE EMAIL WAS NOT RECEIVED AT THE TIME BECAUSE IT WAS SENT AFTER STANDARD WORK HOURS. WHILE STOPPED IN TRAFFIC ON I-65 NEAR THE JAMES ROBERTSON PARKWAY EXIT, THE DRIVER NOTICED A LEAK FROM THE BACK OF THE TANKER IN HIS REAR VIEW MIRROR AND PULLED OVER TO INSPECT FURTHER. NO HOLES OR CRACKS WERE OBSERVED, BUT PRODUCT WAS LEAKING FROM THE TANKER.  THE DRIVER ATTEMPTED TO STOP THE LEAK, BUT WAS UNSUCCESSFUL. EMERGENCY RESPONDERS WERE CALLED TO THE SCENE AND USED STOP GAP MEASURES TO STOP THE FLOW OF PRODUCT. PALM FREIGHT CONTACTED A HAZ MAT RESPONDER, BUT WHEN THEY DID NOT REPORT TO THE SCENE IMMEDIATELY, PALM FREIGHT ENGAGED THE SERVICES OF A HAZ MAT RESPONDER WHO WAS AT THE SCENE. LIME WAS INITIALLY USED IN AN EFFORT TO NEUTRALIZE THE SPILL, BUT THE HAZ MAT RESPONDER INDICATED THAT SODA ASH WAS PREFERRED, SO PALM FREIGHT OBTAINED SODA ASH FROM CONSIGNEE, WHICH WAS USED FOR FINAL NEUTRALIZATION. SOME TIME AFTER THE LEAK WAS STOPPED, OFFICIALS AT THE SCENE ORDERED THE TANKER TRUCK COMBINATION TO RETURN TO THE PALM FREIGHT TERMINAL AT 1234 BRIDGESTONE PARKWAY, AND IT WAS DRIVEN THERE BY ANOTHER COMPANY DRIVER.
column169: PENDING FURTHER INVESTIGATION AND A FINAL DETERMINATION AS TO THE CAUSE OF THE INCIDENT, PALM FREIGHT INTENDS TO TAKE THE FOLLOWING PRECAUTIONARY MEASURES TO PREVENT RECURRENCE: AUDIT LOADING AND EMERGENCY NOTIFICATION PROCEDURES AT NYRSTAR'S FACILITY, REQUIRING IMPROVEMENTS AS NEEDED; CONDUCT RETRAINING OF ALL DRIVERS RELATED TO PRE-TRIP INSPECTIONS AND INTRODUCE MORE DETAILED DRIVER CHECKLISTS AS VERIFICATION OF COMPLIANCE; AND RECHECK ALL EQUIPMENT AND TEST VALVES TO ENSURE PROPER OPERATION.

column168: According to the driver and a witness, our driver was cut off and forced to the side of the road and ultimately drove off the road, leading to a rollover off the roadway.  A passing tow truck driver noticed the wreck, called the police and fire department, who then notified Mid Thumb Trucking.  The driver was taken to a hospital for injuries and the fire department and tow truck vehicles secured the scene until we arrived.  There was no evidence of product leaking from the trailer. A special HAZMAT team was called in to drill the holes in the side of the trailer, and an environmental crew was called in to drain it.  The product that did leak began when a hole was drilled by the HAZMAT team, allowing air to vent into the trailer and release fuel out of a designed relief area called a void hole.  This hole was plugged within a minute or so and no more fuel was spilled.  The environmental crew on-site cleaned up that spill and was in charge of remediation of the scene when the truck/trailer was pulled from it.  The trailer was crushed on the passenger side due to the accident, but did not leak or have any signs of rupture when it was righted and towed away.
column169: The main suggestion to prevent the spillage would be to plug or cork off all void holes or other possible avenues of fuel leakage prior to venting the trailer by drilling holes in it.  Upon inspection, some product (about 250 gallons) was found still in the trailer that could not be pumped out.  That product was drained using the trailer piping (which was also undamaged) and discarded as slop.

column168: Customer on Automatic fill account had delivery made to home by independent contractor McBride Trucking.  Customer switched heating source in home from heating oil to electric and records support that carrier was not notified of the heating conversion.  Subcontractor made delivery to account and filled 2 tanks on property - 1 on the outside of the home and when contractor noticed disconnected line, he filled the tank on the interior of the home. Tank on the interior of the home had been decommisioned sometime in the past.  Tank on the interior of the home held the majority of the product, however, we estimate that 2 gallons of oil leaked from a corroded gauge device on top of the tank.  Customer was not at home for 2 days and when the customer returned they discovered the oil release contained to a stain on their basement floor.  Fumes had permiated throughout the home.  Customer contacted carrier and carrier sent a restoration company and professional remediation company who opened the house up and placed fans in the home.  Professional remediation company indicated the product was a "stain" on the floor. Customer had medical issues and as a result elected to leave the home and stay at a hotel. Customer has since filed a claim with their homeowners carrier and it is our understnading that they will be cutting a portion of the concrete in the basement floor out to remove stain.  The homeowner's insurance carrier has assumed the responsibility to complete the remediation.
column169: Customer account has been terminated to prevent future occurrence.

column168: Incident Background:    On September 2, 2012, at approximately 6:00 am CDT, a tractor-trailer operated by CRST was involved in a roll-over incident. As a result, the cargo shifted releasing an undetermined amount of herbicide, paint, and ink inside the trailer.    Emergency Response:    On September 2, 2012, at approximately 11:26 AM CDT, Mr. Lee Copblentz with CRST  retained Cura Emergency Services (CES) to manage the cleanup operations within the trailer. The CES incident manager contacted Officer Jason Brandy with the Colorado State Patrol Hazmat Patrol to gain additional infonnation about the release. Based on available information, the CES incident manager dispatched a crew from Belfor Environmental to assess the site and perform the corrective actions.    Regulatory Notification:    The release was contained to the interior of the trailer. No sensitive receptors were impacted; therefore no state regulatory notification was necessary. Additionally, on September 2, 2012, at approximately 11:35 am CDT, onsite Colorado State Patrol Hazmat Patrol personnel, Mr. Jason Bandy, advised the CES incident manager no regulatozy notification would be necessary.    Corrective Actions:    Belfor personnel met with Mr. Bandy. Crews donned the proper PPE to make entry into the trailer. Belfor personnel collected and containerized all damaged or leaking herbicide containers into (3) three 55-gallon poly drums for transport and disposal. Damaged and leaking containers of ink and paint were collected and containerized into (14) fourteen 55-gallon drums for transport and disposal. Once all damaged  and leaking products were removed  from the trailer, crews deployed granular absorbents to the trailer's surfaces to solidify any free-standing product. All spent absorbents were collected and containerized into (1) one 55-gallon drum. Belfor personnel wiped all impacted surfaces of the trailer with absorbent pads until no visual or olfactory evidence of ink, paint or herbicide could be observed at the site. The trailer was then up righted and towed from the area. With the site returned to pre-spill conditions, Belfor personnel demobilized from the site.

column168: ON SEPTEMBER 5TH, 2012, AT APPROXIMATELY 3:10 AM, THERE WAS AN OIL SPILL TO THE MISSISSIPPI RIVER FROM THE EXXONMOBIL BATON ROUGE REFINERY DOCK. WHILE DISCHARGING THE MOSCOW UNIVERSITY (DOBA CARGO), THE CONTROLLER NOTICED OIL ON THE DECK OF THE DOCK. THE SUMP SYSTEM BECAME OVERWHELMED, CAUSING CRUDE OIL TO BACK OUT THROUGH THE DRAINS; IT BEGAN ACCUMULATING ON THE DECK OF THE DOCK AND LEAKED INTO THE MISSISSIPPI RIVER. THIS SPILL RESULTED IN AN EXCEEDANCE OF THE LDEQ REPORTABLE QUANTITY FOR OIL TO WATER. LDEQ ENVIRONMENTAL SCIENTIST RACHEL MROCH MONITORED THE EVENT THROUGH A SITE VISIT. THERE WERE NO INJURIES AS A RESULT OF THIS INCIDENT.

column168: Railcar GATX #95781 arrived at Tampa TRANSFLO terminal on 9/19/2012. Arrival Inspection was conducted on 9/19/2012 by Terminal Manager. Only documented defect was a missing chain on the sample tube cap. No indications of any defects or releases. Two full truck loads and one partial were taken off railcar GATX 95781 on 9/19/2012; the day before the release. No issues observed during this transfer. There was no release of gas when the gate valve was opened.   The railcar was not being offloaded when the release was discovered on 9/20/2012. The loader was going to connect a vapor recover hose from an empty railcar into GATX 95781. He connected to the empty railcar and as he was going to connect the vapor recovery hose to GATX 95781, he discovered the leak. No issues noted until valve was opened. The terminal and CSX/TRANSFLO notified the local Fire Department  and Hillsborough County EMA.  Emergency response contractor was also deployed onsite to evaluate situation and car was then off-loaded without incident at 13:15.    Temperature was approximately 77 °F at time of release on 9/20/2012. Average temperature on 9/19/2012 was 82 °F.  RESCAR suspects temperature change may have been a factor, but unsure what caused seal to not set properly. Seal on gate valve of the liquid side not seated properly.  RESCAR was not able to repair the valve on-site. Further information on cause may be available when repairs can be made off-site at the railcar repair shop. NGL secured a One-Time Movement Approval (OTMA) from the DOT before releasing railcar to a repair shop.
column169: Awaiting results from repair facility.

A vehicle operated by Clean Harbors Environmental Services, Inc. was en route from the shipper’s location to the intended waste management facility.  During the course of the trip, the driver made a routine stop at a 10 day in-transit facility pending final delivery to the destination facility. While at this  location, it was discovered that material had escaped from the package onto the ground. Facility personnel assembled a response team to enter the trailer and address the source of the leak. Upon inspection, it was discovered that one poly drum had developed a small crack on the bottom of the drum. The crew proceeded to overpack the leaking container, excavate and drum the soil along with all debris and clean-up supplies used to contain the release and decontaminate the trailer floor.  The trailer floor was repaired and placed back in to service. At the conclusion of the response activities, the material was sent to the intended waste management facility where it was accepted and processed without incident.
column169: At the time the container was accepted for transportation, no evidence of damage or leaking was observed.
