AT THE NORFOLK SOUTHERN TRAN-LOAD FACILITY IN DORAVILLE GA, THE ETHANOL CARRIER PULLED AWAY FROM THE ETHANOL PUMP BEFORE ALL THE HOSES WERE REMOVED. THE VAPOR RECOVERY LINE WAS STILL CONNECTED TO THE REAR OF THE TRAILER. THE VAPOR LINE PULLED THE PUMP AND EVENTUALLY BROKE THE BOTTOM ELBOW ON THE RAILCAR CAUSING ETHANOL TO SPILL. RSI LOADER DID NOT FOLLOW SOP'S FOR ETHANOL TRANSFER. HE ALLOWED THE TRUCK DRIVER TO CONNECT AND DISCONNECT HOSES FROM THE PUMP TO THE TRAILER. HE DID NOT UNHOOK THE SCULLY SYSTEM LAST AND LET THE TRAILER MOVE WITH THE VAPOR LINE STILL CONNECTED.
column169: RSI IMMEDIATELY IMPLEMENTED A 2 MAN/PUMP REQUIREMENT. RSI MADE CHANGES TO SOP INCLUDING; DRIVERS ARE NOT TO ASSIST IN ANY WAY, CLOSE THE RAILCAR MAIN VALVE AFTER EACH LOAD, WHEEL CHOCK DRIVER FRONT WHEEL AND PLACE "STOP" SIGN IN DRIVERS WINDOW, BOTH LOADERS INITIAL OFF ON DETAILED CHECKLIST FOR EVERY LOAD.

column168: The customer, Caraustar (Sweetwater), ordered 2 totes of sodium hydroxide (25% solution) and 2 totes of sodium hypochlorite (12.5% solution) to be delivered by E&C Chemicals on 9/20/2012. Upon arrival at the customer's site, our driver was directed away from the loading dock to a parking area near the customer's storage area by the customer. The delivery truck was stopped in an area with a slight incline (~ 2-3 degrees) with the opening of the truck pointing downhill. Each tote was moved from it's secure point on the truck to the rear opening by the E&C driver with a manual pallet jack where the customer would unload each tote from the truck with a forklift. The first 3 totes were unloaded without incident. As the fourth tote was being moved to the rear opening, the momentum carried the package too close to the edge resulting in the tote tipping out of the truck and onto the parking area surface ~(4 - 4.5 feet). Upon impact, the tote ruptured (actually broke into 3 pieces). The duration of the release was immediate and all 330 gallons spilled onto the parking area. Since it was on their property, the customer took control of the spill management by diking and adding enough vermiculite to completely immobilized the spill. I understand they had an outside contractor (on they use all the time) complete the clean up which, I understand, was completed in about 4 hours. I notified our insurance carrier with a quick report (copy attached) as I was expecting a bill for clean up and disposal. Also, the customer indicated they would provide us a copy of their "near miss" report so we would have all the specific details. To date, I have received neither.
column169: We will continue with our hazmat training program which includes DOT regulations (labelling, packaging, etc.). However, as of 10/1/2012, we no longer transport any hazardous or dangerous materials from our facility to our customers, but utilized common carriers for our transportation requirements.

column42: ELEVATED TEMPERATURE LIQUID, N.O.S., AT OR ABOVE 100 C AND BELOW ITS FLASH POINT (INCLUDING MOLTEN METALS, MOLTEN SALTS, ETC.)
column168: PARTY #1 (P-1, OSCAR OSVALDO LARIOS), AN EMPLOYEE AND DRIVER FOR SOUTHWEST TRAILS, A BULK COMMODITIES TRANSPORTATION COMPANY, WAS DRIVING VEHICLE #1 (V-1), A 2005 PETERBILT 3-AXLE TRUCK TRACTOR IN COMBINATION WITH A 2002 POLAR 2-AXLE TANK SEMI-TRAILER. THE TANK TRAILER WAS LOADED WITH 6,232 GALLONS (52,100 LBS.) OF ELEVATED TEMPERATURE LIQUID ASPHALT (350 DEGREES FAHRENHEIT) AND PLACARDED UN 3257. ON 09-15-12, AT 0041 HOURS, P-L LOADED V-1 AT WESTERN REFINING COMPANY, PHOENIX, ARIZONA AND BEGAN DRIVING TO A DELIVERY LOCATION IN PINE VALLEY, CALIFORNIA, FOLLOWING A ROUTE FROM PHOENIX (I-10 W/B) TO BLYTHE (SR 78 W/B) TO BRAWLEY (SR 111 S/B) TO EL CENTRO (I-8 W/B) TO PINE VALLEY, A DISTANCE OF APPROXIMATELY 330 MILES. AT THE TIME OF THE INCIDENT, P-1 WAS TRAVELING ON SR 78 W/B, EAST OF COUNTY ROUTE S34 (OGILBY ROAD). THIS SECTION OF HIGHWAY NEARS THE COLORADO RIVER AND THE ARIZONA BORDER AND PASSES THOUGH THE CIBOLA NATIONAL WILDLIFE REFUGE WHICH HAS A ROLLING HILLS DESERT REGION. THE ROADWAY SHOULDERS ARE NARROW IN MANY PLACES AND THE ROAD HAS DIPS AND TURNS. AT APPROXIMATELY 0700 HOURS, A P-1 TRAVELED ON SR 78 W/B, A LEFT SIDE TIRE ON ONE OF THE TRAILER AXLES DEFLATED. P-1 APPARENTLY WAS UNAWARE OF THE DEFLATED TIRE AND CONTINUED A MINIMUM OF 1.2 MILES BEYOND THE  LOCATION WHERE THE TIRE BEGAN TO DISINTEGRATE, LEAVING SHREDS AND FRICTION MARKS ON THE ROADWAY. THE DEFECTIVE TIRE OVERHEATED AND SUBSEQUENTLY CAUGHT FIRE. WHEN P-1 ATTEMPTED TO EXTINGUISH THE FIRE UNSUCCESSFULLY WITH A FIRE EXTINGUISHER. HE THEN DISCONNECTED THE TRUCK TRACTOR FROM TRAILER AND DROVE THE TRUCK TRACTOR TO SAFE LOCATION OF 500' WEST. P-1 RETREATED TO A SAFE DISTANCE FROM THE FIRE AND ATTEMPTED TO CALL 911, BUT HIS PHONE DID NOT HAVE A SIGNAL. A PASSERBY DID CALL 911 AND REPORT THE INCIDENT. WHEILE THE FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED, THE FIRE CONTINUED TO BURN AND SUBSEQUENTLY MELTED THE REAR SECTION OF THE ALUMINUM TANK WITHIN LESS THAN 30 MINUTES, WHICH RELEASED THE ENTIRE 6,232 GALLON LOAD. THE ELEVATED TEMPERATURE LIQUID ASPHALT FLOWED ONTO THE ROADWAY AND THEN TRAVELED IN BOTH A NORTH AND SOURTH DIRECTION INTO THE OPEN DESERT. BECAUSE THE RELEASE WAS NEAR THE TOP OF A HILL, THE GRAD OF THE TERRAIN SLOPED DOWNWARD FROM THE ROADWAY. THE FLOWING ASPHALT COVERED A 100' WIDE SECTION OF THE ROADWAY, BUT GRAVITY CARRIED THE FLOW DOWN THE EMBANKMENTS ON BOTH THE NORTH AND SOUTH SIDE OF THE ROADWAY AND INTO ESTABLISHED DRY WASH TRIBUTARIES (ALSO REFERRED TO AS SWALES). ON THE NORTH SIDE OF THE ROADY, THE ASPHALT FLOWED A DISTANCE OF 125' AND POOLED IN A 25' X 75' AREA. ON THE SOUTH SIDE OF THE ROADWAY, THE ASPHALT FLOWED IN TWO DISTINCT ROUTES, ONE RUNNING NARROWLY IN A SOUTHEAST DIRECTION FOR 700' AND THE OTHER RUNNING NARROWLY IN A SOUTHERLY DIRECTION FOR 900'.    0706 HOURS, WINTERHAVEN CHP UNIT 116-63, OFFICER SAPP RECEIVED A CALL FROM EL CENTRO COMMUNICATION CENTER OF SEMI-TRUCK ON FIRE ON SR 78, E/OF OBILBY ROAD.    0708 HOURS, OFFICER SAPP WAS ADVISED THE VEHICLE FIRE INVOLVE

column168: A KEMIRA DRIVER REPORTED TO THE KEMIRA MANUFACTURING FACILITY IN ORDER TO LOAD A SHIPMENT OF FERRIC CHLORIDE TO BE DELIVERED TO A CUSTOMER IN BALTIMORE. UPON THE COMPLETION OF LOADING THE TRAILER, THE RELEASE VALVE ON THE TRAILER WAS LEFT IN THE OPEN POSITION BY THE DRIVER IN ERROR. AS THE DRIVER TRAVELED THE 2.96 MILES FROM THE LOADING POINT TO THE CUSTOMER, A 1 TO 4 FOOT TRAIL OF FERRIC CHLORIDE WAS RELEASED FROM THE TRAILER FROM THE OPEN RELEASE VALVE. BECAUSE THE TRAILER WAS NOT PRESSURIZED, THE TRAIL FROM THE LIQUID WAS INTERMITTENT. AN EMPLOYEE FROM THE KEMIRA MANUFACTURING FACILITY NOTICED THE TRAIL OF FERRIC CHLORIDE ON THE STREET JUST OUTSIDE THE FACILITY. HE IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED THE DISPATCHER RESPONSIBLE FOR THE LOAD. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS CONTACTED, AS WELL AT THE KEMIRA EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED FIRST, SPREADING ABSORBENT MATERIAL ONTO THE LIQUID RELEASED. THE KEMIRA EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR ARRIVED AT THE SCENE AT 13:45, AND BEGAN THE CLEANUP OF THE ABSORBENT MATERIAL. THE CLEANUP WAS COMPLETED BY 18:00 THAT DAY.
column169: THE TRAILER INVOLVED IN THE SPILL HAS BEEN MOVED TO THE KEMIRA LOGISTICS, INC. MAINTENANCE FACILITY IN EUCLID, OH. THE RELEASE VALVE WHICH WAS LEFT OPEN IS BEING REPLACED WITH AN AIR ACTUATED VALVE WHICH AUTOMATICALLY CLOSES WHEN AIR HAS BEEN APPLIED TO THE TRAILER. THIS WILL PREVENT A RECURRENCE OF THIS INCIDENT.
